{"title_page": "Fourth Inspectorate-General (Turkey)", "text_new": "{{Infobox subdivision\n| name                            = Fourth Inspectorate-General\n| official_name                   = D\u00f6rd\u00fcnc\u00fc Umumi M\u00fcffeti\u015flik\n| established_title               = Establishment\n| established_date                = January 1936\n| native_name                     = \n| settlement_type                 = Inspectorate-General\n| leader_title                    = Governor-Commander\n| leader_name                     = Abdullah Alpdo\u011fan\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| seat                            = [[Elaz\u0131\u011f]]\n| extinct_date                    = 1952\n| extinct_title                   = Disestablishment\n| subdivision_type1               = Provinces\n| subdivision_name                = [[Turkey]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Bing\u00f6l Province|Bing\u00f6l]]<br>[[Tunceli province|Tunceli]]<br>\n[[Elaz\u0131\u011f province|Elaz\u0131g]]<br>[[Erzincan Province|Erz\u0131ncan]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Fourth Inspectorate-General''' (''D\u00f6rd\u00fcnc\u00fc Umumi M\u00fcffeti\u015flik'') refers to a regional administrative subdivision<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Bayir|first=Derya|title=Minorities and Nationalism in Turkish Law|date=2016-04-22|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-317-09579-8|location=|pages=139-141|language=en}}</ref> in the Dersim region. \n\n== History ==\nThe Fourth [[Inspectorates-General (Turkey)|Inspectorate-General]]  (''Umumi M\u00fcfetti\u015flik,'' UM) is based on the Law 1164 from September 1927,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://dergipark.org.tr/en/download/article-file/20607|title=\u00dc\u00e7\u00fcnc\u00fc Umumi M\u00fcfetti\u015fli\u011fi'nin Kurulmas\u0131 ve III. Umum\u00ee M\u00fcfetti\u015f Tahsin Uzer'in Baz\u0131 \u00d6nemli Faaliyetleri|last=|first=|date=|website=Dergipark|page=2|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> which was passed in order to [[Turkification|Turkefy]] the non-Turkish population.<ref name=\":0\" /> Before, there were established three other [[Inspectorates-General (Turkey)|Inspectorates-General]] in other areas. The first in Kurdish provinces in the southeast of Anatolia, the second in Thracia in the western part of Turkey,<ref>{{Cite book|last=G\u00f6\u00e7ek|first=Fatma M\u00fcge|title=Contested Spaces in Contemporary Turkey: Environmental, Urban and Secular Politics|date=30 June 2017|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|year=|isbn=978-1-78673-228-6|location=|pages=102|language=en}}</ref> and another one in northeastern part of Turkey.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jongerden|first=Joost|title=The Settlement Issue in Turkey and the Kurds: An Analysis of Spatial Policies, Modernity and War|date=28 May 2007|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-474-2011-8|location=|pages=53|language=en}}</ref> Following the Tunceli Law of December 1935,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://dersim-massacre-1937-1938.html/|title=Dersim Massacre, 1937-1938 {{!}} Sciences Po Mass Violence and Resistance - Research Network|date=2016-01-19|website=dersim-massacre-1937-1938.html|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> which demanded a more powerful government in the region,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Y\u0131lmaz|first=Kamil|title=Disengaging from Terrorism - Lessons from the Turkish Penitents|date=2014-04-16|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-317-96449-0|location=|pages=26|language=en}}</ref> and also classified the Dersim district from the [[Elaz\u0131\u011f Province|Elazi\u011f]] province into a province named [[Tunceli Province|Tunceli]],<ref name=\":2\" /> the fourth [[Inspectorates-General (Turkey)|Inspectorate-General]] was created in January 1936.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cagaptay|first=Soner|title=Islam, Secularism and Nationalism in Modern Turkey: Who is a Turk?|date=2 May 2006|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-134-17448-5|location=|pages=108\u2013110|language=en}}</ref> The fourth UM span over the provinces of Elazi\u011f, [[Erzincan Province|Erzincan]], [[Bing\u00f6l Province|Bing\u00f6l]] and [[Tunceli Province|Tunceli]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The focus of the UM was on Tunceli but its seat was in [[Elaz\u0131\u011f|Elazi\u011f]].<ref name=\"\u00c7a\u011faptay\">Soner \u00c7a\u01e7aptay, ''Islam, Secularism, and Nationalism in Modern Turkey: Who is a Turk?'', Taylor & Francis, 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-415-38458-2}}, p. 48</ref> It was governed by a Governor-Commander in a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dersim-massacre-1937-1938.html/|title=Dersim Massacre, 1937-1938 {{!}} Sciences Po Mass Violence and Resistance - Research Network|last=Kieser|first=Hans-Lukas|date=19 January 2016|website=dersim-massacre-1937-1938.html|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Most of the employees in the municipality were to be filled with military personnel and the Governor-Commander had the authority to evacuate whole villages and resettle them in other parts.<ref name=\":0\" /> Also the juridical guarantees did not comply with the law in the other parts in Turkey. The trials were at most 15 days long and sentences could not be appealed. For a release, the Governor Commander had to give his consent. The application of the death penalty was under the authority of the Governor-Commander, while normally it would be the authority of the Grand National Assembly of Turkey to approve such a punishment.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first Governor-Commander was {{Interlanguage link|Abdullah Alpdo\u011fan|lt=|tr||WD=}}, the nephew of [[Nureddin Pasha|Nurettin Pasha]], who defeated the rebels who led the [[Ko\u00e7giri rebellion]] in 1921.<ref name=\":2\" /> Following, to gain more control over the region, military quarters, police stations, schools and also a railway track to [[Elaz\u0131\u011f|Elazi\u011f]] were built. [[Seyid Riza]], a local tribal chief, demanded the Tunceli Law to be revoked<ref name=\":2\" /> and tribesmen loyal to him attacked a police station in March 1937 which sparked a strong response from the Turkish Government.<ref name=\":2\" />  The rebellion was suppressed with outmost determination, massacres of the local population were executed and its leaders were hanged.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Abdullah Alpdo\u011fan supported the idea, the Kurdish identity would be toppled by telling the Kurds just enough that they were Turks,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Aslan|first=Senem|title=Nation Building in Turkey and Morocco|date=2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2015|isbn=978-1-107-05460-8|location=|pages=64|language=en}}</ref> and stayed in the post of the Governor-Commander until 1943.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tunceli.gov.tr/hukumet-konagi-tarihce|title=H\u00fck\u00fcmet Kona\u011f\u0131 Tarih\u00e7e|website=www.tunceli.gov.tr|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Disestablishment ===\nIn 1946 the Tunceli Law was abolished and the state of emergency removed but the authority of the fourth UM was transferred to the military.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1948 the administrative posts of the UM were not to be reoccupied but the possibility of the creation was kept. By 1950 a discussion about the UMs had begun by several members of the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey]], Remzi Bucak from [[Diyarbak\u0131r Province|Diyarbakir]], criticized the UM and compared it to the British colonization practices in [[British India|India]]. The Inspectorates-General were eventually dissolved in 1952 during the Government of the [[Democrat Party (Turkey, 1946\u201361)|Democrat Party]] who had a different approach to the Kurdish question.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Fleet|first=Kate|title=The Cambridge History of Turkey|last2=Kunt|first2=I. Metin|last3=Kasaba|first3=Re\u015fat|last4=Faroqhi|first4=Suraiya|date=2008-04-17|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-521-62096-3|location=|pages=343|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:History of Erzincan Province]]\n[[Category:History of Tunceli Province]]\n[[Category:History of Bing\u00f6l Province]]\n[[Category:History of Elaz\u0131\u011f Province]]\n[[Category:Dersim rebellion]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox subdivision\n| name                            = Fourth Inspectorate-General\n| official_name                   = D\u00f6rd\u00fcnc\u00fc Umumi M\u00fcffeti\u015flik\n| established_title               = Establishment\n| established_date                = January 1936\n| native_name                     = \n| settlement_type                 = Inspectorate-General\n| leader_title                    = Governor-Commander\n| leader_name                     = Abdullah Alpdo\u011fan\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| seat                            = [[Elaz\u0131\u011f]]\n| extinct_date                    = 1952\n| extinct_title                   = Disestablishment\n| subdivision_type1               = Provinces\n| subdivision_name                = [[Turkey]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Bing\u00f6l Province|Bing\u00f6l]]<br>[[Tunceli province|Tunceli]]<br>\n[[Elaz\u0131\u011f province|Elaz\u0131g]]<br>[[Erzincan Province|Erz\u0131ncan]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Fourth Inspectorate-General''' (''D\u00f6rd\u00fcnc\u00fc Umumi M\u00fcffeti\u015flik'') refers to a regional administrative subdivision<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Bayir|first=Derya|title=Minorities and Nationalism in Turkish Law|date=2016-04-22|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-317-09579-8|location=|pages=139-141|language=en}}</ref> in the Dersim region. \n\n== History ==\nThe Fourth [[Inspectorates-General (Turkey)|Inspectorate-General]] (''Umumi M\u00fcfetti\u015flik,'' UM) is based on the Law 1164 from September 1927,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://dergipark.org.tr/en/download/article-file/20607|title=\u00dc\u00e7\u00fcnc\u00fc Umumi M\u00fcfetti\u015fli\u011fi'nin Kurulmas\u0131 ve III. Umum\u00ee M\u00fcfetti\u015f Tahsin Uzer'in Baz\u0131 \u00d6nemli Faaliyetleri|last=|first=|date=|website=Dergipark|page=2|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> which was passed in order to [[Turkification|Turkefy]] the non-Turkish population.<ref name=\":0\" /> Before, there were established three other [[Inspectorates-General (Turkey)|Inspectorates-General]] in other areas. The first in Kurdish provinces in the southeast of Anatolia, the second in Thracia in the western part of Turkey,<ref>{{Cite book|last=G\u00f6\u00e7ek|first=Fatma M\u00fcge|title=Contested Spaces in Contemporary Turkey: Environmental, Urban and Secular Politics|date=30 June 2017|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|year=|isbn=978-1-78673-228-6|location=|pages=102|language=en}}</ref> and another one in northeastern part of Turkey.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Jongerden|first=Joost|title=The Settlement Issue in Turkey and the Kurds: An Analysis of Spatial Policies, Modernity and War|date=28 May 2007|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-474-2011-8|location=|pages=53|language=en}}</ref> Following the Tunceli Law of December 1935,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://dersim-massacre-1937-1938.html/|title=Dersim Massacre, 1937-1938 {{!}} Sciences Po Mass Violence and Resistance - Research Network|date=2016-01-19|website=dersim-massacre-1937-1938.html|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> which demanded a more powerful government in the region,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Y\u0131lmaz|first=Kamil|title=Disengaging from Terrorism - Lessons from the Turkish Penitents|date=2014-04-16|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-317-96449-0|location=|pages=26|language=en}}</ref> and also classified the Dersim district from the [[Elaz\u0131\u011f Province|Elazi\u011f]] province into a province named [[Tunceli Province|Tunceli]],<ref name=\":2\" /> the fourth [[Inspectorates-General (Turkey)|Inspectorate-General]] was created in January 1936.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cagaptay|first=Soner|title=Islam, Secularism and Nationalism in Modern Turkey: Who is a Turk?|date=2 May 2006|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-134-17448-5|location=|pages=108\u2013110|language=en}}</ref> The fourth UM span over the provinces of Elazi\u011f, [[Erzincan Province|Erzincan]], [[Bing\u00f6l Province|Bing\u00f6l]] and [[Tunceli Province|Tunceli]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The focus of the UM was on Tunceli but its seat was in [[Elaz\u0131\u011f|Elazi\u011f]].<ref name=\"\u00c7a\u011faptay\">Soner \u00c7a\u01e7aptay, ''Islam, Secularism, and Nationalism in Modern Turkey: Who is a Turk?'', Taylor & Francis, 2006, {{ISBN|978-0-415-38458-2}}, p. 48</ref> It was governed by a Governor-Commander in a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dersim-massacre-1937-1938.html/|title=Dersim Massacre, 1937-1938 {{!}} Sciences Po Mass Violence and Resistance - Research Network|last=Kieser|first=Hans-Lukas|date=19 January 2016|website=dersim-massacre-1937-1938.html|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Most of the employees in the municipality were to be filled with military personnel and the Governor-Commander had the authority to evacuate whole villages and resettle them in other parts.<ref name=\":0\" /> Also the juridical guarantees did not comply with the law in the other parts in Turkey. The trials were at most 15 days long and sentences could not be appealed. For a release, the Governor Commander had to give his consent. The application of the death penalty was under the authority of the Governor-Commander, while normally it would be the authority of the Grand National Assembly of Turkey to approve such a punishment.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first Governor-Commander was {{Interlanguage link|Abdullah Alpdo\u011fan|lt=|tr||WD=}}, the nephew of [[Nureddin Pasha|Nurettin Pasha]], who defeated the rebels who led the [[Ko\u00e7giri rebellion]] in 1921.<ref name=\":2\" /> Following, to gain more control over the region, military quarters, police stations, schools and also a railway track to [[Elaz\u0131\u011f|Elazi\u011f]] were built. [[Seyid Riza]], a local tribal chief, demanded the Tunceli Law to be revoked<ref name=\":2\" /> and tribesmen loyal to him attacked a police station in March 1937 which sparked a strong response from the Turkish Government.<ref name=\":2\" />  The rebellion was suppressed with outmost determination, massacres were executed and its leaders were hanged.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> Abdullah Alpdo\u011fan supported the idea, the Kurdish identity would be toppled by telling the Kurds just enough that they were Turks, <ref>{{Cite book|last=Aslan|first=Senem|title=Nation Building in Turkey and Morocco|date=2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2015|isbn=978-1-107-05460-8|location=|pages=64|language=en}}</ref> and stayed in the post of the Governor-Commander until 1943.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tunceli.gov.tr/hukumet-konagi-tarihce|title=H\u00fck\u00fcmet Kona\u011f\u0131 Tarih\u00e7e|website=www.tunceli.gov.tr|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Disestablishment ===\nIn 1946 the Tunceli Law was abolished and the state of emergency removed but the authority of the fourth UM was transferred to the military.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1948 the administrative posts of the UM were not to be reoccupied but the possibility of the creation was kept. By 1950 a discussion about the UMs had begun by several members of the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey]], Remzi Bucak from [[Diyarbak\u0131r Province|Diyarbakir]], criticized the UM and compared it to the British colonization practices in [[British India|India]]. The Inspectorates-General were eventually dissolved in 1952 during the Government of the [[Democrat Party (Turkey, 1946\u201361)|Democrat Party]] who had a different approach to the Kurdish question.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Fleet|first=Kate|title=The Cambridge History of Turkey|last2=Kunt|first2=I. Metin|last3=Kasaba|first3=Re\u015fat|last4=Faroqhi|first4=Suraiya|date=2008-04-17|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-521-62096-3|location=|pages=