{"title_page": "David James (footballer, born 1970)", "text_new": "{{short description|English footballer born 1970}}\n{{for|other footballers named \"David James\"|David James (disambiguation){{!}}David James}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = David James  <br /> <small>[[Order of the British Empire|MBE]]</small>\n| image = DaJa.JPG\n| image_size = \n| caption = David James in 2009\n| fullname = David Benjamin James<ref>{{cite web|title=FIFA World Cup South Africa 2010 \u2013 List of Players|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/22/85/78/fwc_2010_squadlists.pdf|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association (FIFA)|accessdate=8 June 2013}}</ref>\n| height = {{height|m=1.94|precision=0}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/bsp/hi/football/statistics/players/j/james_1881.stm |title=BBC profile |work=BBC Sport |date=1 August 1970 |accessdate=20 June 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1970|8|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Welwyn Garden City]], [[Hertfordshire|Herts]], England\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = 1986\u20131988\n| youthclubs1 = [[Watford F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Watford]]\n| years1 = 1988\u20131992\n| clubs1 = [[Watford F.C.|Watford]]\n| caps1 = 89\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1992\u20131999\n| clubs2 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps2 = 214\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 1999\u20132001\n| clubs3 = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n| caps3 = 67\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2001\u20132004\n| clubs4 = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]\n| caps4 = 91\n| goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2004\u20132006\n| clubs5 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n| caps5 = 93\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2006\u20132010\n| clubs6 = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]\n| caps6 = 134\n| goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2010\u20132012\n| clubs7 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n| caps7 = 81\n| goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs8 = [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]]\n| caps8 = 19\n| goals8 = 0\n| years9 = 2013\n| clubs9 = [[\u00cd\u00fer\u00f3ttabandalag Vestmannaeyja|\u00cdBV Vestmannaeyjar]]\n| caps9 = 17\n| goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2014\n| clubs10 = [[Kerala Blasters FC|Kerala Blasters]]\n| caps10 = 12\n| goals10 = 0\n| totalcaps = 826\n| totalgoals = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 1990\u20131992\n| nationalteam1 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 10\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1994\u20131996\n| nationalteam2 = [[England B national football team|England B]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 2\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 1997\u20132010\n| nationalteam3 = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 53\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2014\n| managerclubs1 = [[Kerala Blasters FC|Kerala Blasters]] (player-manager)\n| manageryears2 = 2018\n| managerclubs2 = [[Kerala Blasters FC|Kerala Blasters]]\n| club-update = \n}}\n\n'''David Benjamin James''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (born 1 August 1970) is an English former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]]. His most recent position was manager at [[Kerala Blasters FC]] in the [[Indian Super League]] in 2018. He is also a pundit on [[BT Sport]]'s football coverage.\n\nJames is fourth on the [[List of Premier League players|list of all-time Premier League appearances]], having played in 572 top-level matches, and held the Premier League [[Football records in England#Goalkeepers|record for most clean sheets]] with 169 until [[Petr \u010cech]] surpassed this record.<ref>{{cite web | title = Petr Cech breaks Premier League clean sheet record in Arsenal's win over Bournemouth | url = http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11670/10113138/petr-cech-breaks-premier-league-clean-sheet-record-in-arsenals-win-over-bournemouth | accessdate =28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was capped 53 times by [[England national football team|England]] between 1997 and 2010, and was first choice goalkeeper during the team's [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]] and the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] campaigns. He was appointed a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the 2012 Birthday Honours for services to football and charity.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=60173 |supp=y|page=17|date=16 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"MBE\">{{cite news|title=Queen's Birthday Honours list for Bristol|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-18457893|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 June 2012|date=16 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nHaving started his career with [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], James went on to feature in the [[Premier League]] for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]. He gained a [[Football League Cup]] winner's medal with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in [[1994\u201395 FA Cup|1995]], an [[FA Cup]] winner's medal with [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in [[2007\u201308 FA Cup|2008]], as well as runners-up medals with [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in [[1999\u20132000 FA Cup|2000]], Liverpool in [[1995\u201396 FA Cup|1996]] and Portsmouth in [[2009\u201310 FA Cup|2010]]. In 2010, at the age of 39, he became the oldest goalkeeper to appear in an [[FA Cup Final]].<ref name=\"OldestKeeperFACup\">{{cite news|title=FA Cup final as it happened|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8683314.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=15 May 2010|date=18 April 2014|first=Jonathan|last=Stevenson}}</ref> James dropped down a division in 2010 to play for [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] and later played for [[Football League One|League One]] side [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]]. He joined Icelandic side [[\u00cdBV Vestmannaeyjar]] in 2013 in a joint playing and coaching capacity, before officially retiring.\n\nIn October 2013, James took up a coaching position at [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]], the club he has supported since his childhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bedfordtoday.co.uk/sport/football/updated-ex-england-keeper-david-james-helps-to-take-training-with-the-hatters-1-5621216 |title=UPDATED: Ex-England keeper David James helps to take training with the Hatters |work=Bedford Today |publisher = Johnston Publishing Ltd |date= 26 October 2013 |accessdate=26 October 2013}}</ref> The following year, he became the marquee player and manager of the newly formed Kerala Blasters.\n\nJames returned at the helm of affairs of [[Kerala Blasters]], a day after the [[Indian Super League]] side sacked [[Rene Meulensteen]] as their head coach following a string of poor performances by the team on 3 January 2018.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/david-james-returns-as-kerala-blasters-head-coach/articleshow/62353633.cms|title=David James returns as Kerala Blasters head coach}}</ref> James was himself dismissed in December 2018, following an 11-match winless run.<ref name=Goal>{{cite web |last1=Easwar |first1=Nisanth |title=ISL: Kerala Blasters part ways with David James |url=https://www.goal.com/en-in/news/kerala-blasters-part-ways-with-david-james/1ijredv9tg5l11blfq7vh5vp83 |website=Goal |accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Watford===\nBorn in [[Welwyn Garden City]], [[Hertfordshire]], James grew up supporting [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]].<ref>{{cite news\n|title=How on earth did Portsmouth get into this mess?\n|last=James\n|first=David\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2009/aug/16/david-james-portsmouth-takeover-finances\n|work=[[The Guardian]]\n|location=London\n|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group|Guardian News and Media]]\n|date=16 August 2009\n|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|title=David James says England's World Cup base left no room to relax\n|last=Hopkinson\n|first=Tom\n|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/david-james-says-englands-world-1701210\n|work=[[Daily Mirror]]\n|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]\n|location=London\n|date=9 October 2011\n|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref> He signed as a trainee with Luton's [[Luton Town F.C.\u2013Watford F.C. rivalry|local rivals]] [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] upon leaving school, and was first selected for the club's senior team in 1989. In his days as a youth player, he helped Watford win the [[FA Youth Cup]].<ref name=\"globeandmail\">{{cite news\n |title=No.1 David James \n |url=http://stats.globesports.com/EPL/players.asp?player=3128l \n |newspaper=Globe and Mail \n |accessdate=26 August 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927215818/http://stats.globesports.com/EPL/players.asp?player=3128l \n |archivedate=27 September 2007 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> Following the departure of [[Tony Coton]], James made his league debut on 25 August 1990 in a 1\u20132 defeat against [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]], and his performance resulted in an [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] call-up for a match against the [[Republic of Ireland under-21 national football team|Republic of Ireland]]. He earned a total of ten caps for the U21s.\n\nAt club level, James made 89 first-team appearances for Watford, and was named the club's [[List of Watford F.C. Players of the Season|Player of the Season]] for the [[1990\u201391 in English football|1990\u201391 season]], when he kept goal in all 46 [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] games as Watford escaped relegation. He was signed for \u00a31.25m by [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 6 July 1992.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Watford Football Club Illustrated Who's Who|author=Jones, Trefor|year=1996|isbn= 0-9527458-0-1|page=129}}</ref> In 2008, James was inducted into the Watford Hall of Fame for his services to the club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hall of fame |url=http://www.watfordfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10400~1296988,00.html |accessdate=29 May 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506191337/http://www.watfordfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10400~1296988%2C00.html |archivedate=6 May 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Liverpool===\nJames made his Liverpool debut on 16 August 1992 in a 0\u20131 league defeat to [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-sheringhams-sweet-touch-heroic-james-refuses-to-wilt-before-forest-fire-1540943.html|title=Sheringham's sweet touch: Heroic James refuses to wilt before Forest fire |date=17 August 1992|work=The Independent|accessdate=15 June 2011|location=London|first=Joe|last=Lovejoy}}</ref> After conceding twenty goals in eleven matches in the first half of the [[1993\u201394 in English football|1993\u201394]], he was dropped in favour of veteran [[Bruce Grobbelaar]], but was recalled to the starting line-up and kept his first clean sheet of the season in a 1\u20130 away win over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 31 January 1993, which included a penalty save from [[Paul Merson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lfchistory.net/SeasonArchive/Game/1891|title=Arsenal 0 \u2013 1 Liverpool |accessdate=8 August 2016|work=lfchistory.net}}</ref> He also received a runners-up medal in [[1996 FA Cup Final|1996]] in the FA Cup while being on the losing side against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].\n\nJames rose to fame together with Liverpool teammates [[Steve McManaman]], [[Jamie Redknapp]], and [[Robbie Fowler]], who were nicknamed the \"[[Spice Boys (footballers)|Spice Boys]]\" \u2013 an epithet named after the [[Spice Girls]] that was used by those who alleged the Liverpool team of the 1990s were more focused on partying than winning games. James' frequent blunders earned him the nickname ''[[Calamity James]]''. He put down his spate of errors to an overindulgence in playing computer games that in turn affected his concentration.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web| title = 100 Best Moments of PlayStation| url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=128349&site=psw| publisher = Future plc| accessdate =22 April 2009}}</ref> Despite winning the 1995 [[Football League Cup]], James' hold on the starting position was put in jeopardy with the acquisition of [[Brad Friedel]]. On 23 June 1999, after 277 games for Liverpool, he was sold to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] for \u00a31.8&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news| title = David James| url = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/world/players/11/| publisher = CNN| accessdate =26 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Aston Villa===\nJames made his Villa debut on 7 August 1999, and kept a clean sheet in a 1\u20130 away win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in the opening [[Premier League]] game. He was decisive in a penalty [[Penalty shootout (football)|shoot-out]] against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] in the 2000 [[FA Cup]] semi-final, but was at fault for [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]'s winning goal in the ensuing final, the last to be staged at the [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|old Wembley]].\n\nAfter just two years and 85 appearances, James moved to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] for \u00a33.5 million on 11 July 2001, signing a four-year contract.<ref name=\"thisislondon\">{{cite web| title = James completes Hammers move| url = http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/sport/article-1060496-details/James%20completes%20Hammers%20move/article.do| archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/5mscisBqW?url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/sport/article-1060496-details/James%20completes%20Hammers%20move/article.do| url-status=dead| archive-date = 18 January 2010| publisher = This Is London| accessdate = 26 August 2007| df = dmy-all}}</ref> However, a serious knee injury sustained while on international duty kept him out for several months.<ref name=\"knee injury\">{{cite web| title = James anguish over England injury| url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/archive/england/news/2001/0817/20010817engjamesavfc.html| archive-url = https://archive.today/20100118185154/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/archive/england/news/2001/0817/20010817engjamesavfc.html| url-status=dead| archivedate = 18 January 2010| publisher = ESPN| accessdate =26 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n===West Ham United===\nJames made his debut for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] on 24 November 2001 in a 1\u20130 home loss to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/cc_championship/westham/reports/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/01/11/24/SOCCER_West_Ham.html&TEAMHD=westham&DIV=nat1&TEAM=WEST--HAM&RH=West--Ham&PREV_SEASON=2000 |title=West Ham 0 Tottenham 1 |publisher=Sportinglife.com |accessdate=20 June 2010}}{{dead link|date=November 2016}}</ref> In [[2002\u201303 Premier League|2002\u201303]], West Ham were relegated to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]]. James stayed with West Ham at the start of the [[2003\u201304 Football League First Division|2003\u201304 season]] before returning to the Premier League, signing for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on 14 January 2004 for an undisclosed fee as a replacement for the retired [[David Seaman]].<ref name=\"undisclosed\">{{cite news| title = City snap up James with Pardew set to reinvest| url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20040115/ai_n9687915| newspaper = Independent| accessdate =26 August 2007}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Keegan splashes on old spice |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/3395771.stm |work=BBC Sport |date=14 January 2004 |accessdate=29 August 2007 | first=Phil | last=McNulty}}</ref> He played 102 total games in all competitions for West Ham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=2&ham=759&united=David_James |title=Welcome to the Wonderful World of West Ham United Statistics David James |publisher=Westhamstats.info |accessdate=20 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Manchester City===\n{{Quote box\n| quote = \"It was, to put it mildly, the most eccentric of finales. There were still two minutes of normal time remaining, plus five for stoppages, when [manager] [[Stuart Pearce]], adopting a form of leadership that would have been wacky even by [[Brian Clough]]'s standards, had the brainwave of replacing a midfielder, [[Claudio Reyna]], with his reserve goalkeeper, [[Nicky Weaver]], and ordering David James to play as a centre-forward. Amazingly the disorder almost paid off. With James charging around like a headless ostrich, his cameo role incorporating a hilarious air-shot and at least two horrendously late but probably well-meant chops at [[Doriva]]'s legs, the hitherto wretched referee [[Rob Styles]] decreed that [[Joey Barton]]'s centre had flicked off [[Franck Queudrue]]'s hand for a penalty.\"\n| source = \u2014Football journalist [[Daniel Taylor (journalist)|Daniel Taylor]], describing David James brief 6-minute cameo as a striker against Middlesbrough in the post-match report<ref>{{cite web |title=Psycho brainwave takes City to the brink |last=Taylor |first=Daniel |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/may/16/match.manchestercity | website = The Guardian | date = 16 May 2005 | accessdate = 5 January 2018}}</ref>\n| align = right\n| width =40%\n}}\nJames made his [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] debut on 17 January 2004 in a 1\u20131 home draw with [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Man City 1\u20131 Blackburn| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3385507.stm\n| publisher = BBC| accessdate =27 August 2007 | date=17 January 2004}}</ref> City won only four of the seventeen matches that James started, two of which came after James saved penalties against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] and [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dunne salutes City saviour |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/manchester_city/s/115/115128_dunne_salutes_city_saviour.html |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |accessdate=27 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927193041/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/manchester_city/s/115/115128_dunne_salutes_city_saviour.html |archivedate=27 September 2007 }}</ref> James said that exploring the field of [[sport psychology]] improved his skills as a goalkeeper, particularly saving penalty kicks.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/mar/30/football.comment | title=Goalkeeper's fear of the penalty? Not for me | work=The Guardian | location=London | first=David | last=James | date=30 March 2008 | accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn the last day of the [[2004\u201305 FA Premier League|2004\u201305 season]], James was playing for City who needed to beat [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] to qualify for the [[2005\u201306 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] at the opposition's expense. With five minutes remaining the score was 1\u20131, when City's manager [[Stuart Pearce]] replaced midfielder [[Claudio Reyna]] with the substitute goalkeeper [[Nicky Weaver]], and James was moved to play in attack for the remainder of the game. The unusual tactic almost worked when, in [[injury time]], Middlesbrough defender [[Franck Queudrue]] conceded a penalty by handling a cross that was aimed at James. However, [[Robbie Fowler]]'s penalty was saved by Middlesbrough goalkeeper [[Mark Schwarzer]] and so Middlesbrough not City qualified for the UEFA Cup.<ref>{{cite news |title=City pay the penalty for Fowler miss |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2359695/City-pay-the-penalty-for-Fowler-miss.html |work=Telegraph|date=16 May 2005 |accessdate=19 May 2009 | location=London | first=Tim | last=Rich}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August 2006, James, who had separated from his wife, stated that he needed to leave Manchester City to be closer to his children, who lived in London. Manchester City confirmed they had accepted a bid from [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]].<ref name=\"pompey bid\">{{cite news\n |title=City accept James bid \n |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/manchester_city/s/220/220393_city_accept_james_bid.html \n |newspaper=Manchester Evening News \n |accessdate=26 August 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930170949/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/manchester_city/s/220/220393_city_accept_james_bid.html \n |archivedate=30 September 2007 \n}}</ref> Two days later, he joined Portsmouth for \u00a31.2 million, signing a two-year deal.<ref name=\"pompey move\">{{cite news|title=James seals Pompey switch |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/manchester_city/s/220/220500_james_seals_pompey_switch.html |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |accessdate=26 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930165023/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/manchester_city/s/220/220500_james_seals_pompey_switch.html |archivedate=30 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Portsmouth===\n[[File:David James warmup 2010 FA Cup Final 2.jpg|thumb|upright|James during his time at Portsmouth]]\nJames kept clean sheets in his first five appearances for Portsmouth.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Portsmouth finally concede (and have never seemed to stop) but look to join the 20-club| url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20060930/ai_n16762929\n| newspaper = Independent| accessdate =27 August 2007}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> On 22 April 2007, James kept his 142nd [[FA Premier League|Premier League]] clean sheet in a goalless draw with Aston Villa, breaking the record of 141 previously held by [[David Seaman]].<ref>''[http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6555255.stm Aston Villa 0\u20130 Portsmouth]''</ref> At the end of [[2006\u201307 Portsmouth F.C. season|2006\u201307]], James was named Portsmouth's [[Portsmouth F.C.#Portsmouth Player of the Season (since 1968)|player of the season]].\n\nJames has made the most league appearances<ref>[http://stats.premierleague.com/panel_b_alltime.query?q=goalkeeper_clean_sheets_all_seasons&start=1 Premier League official appearance stats]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> of any goalkeeper since the formation of the Premier League over fifteen seasons, in addition to conceding the most goals.<ref>[http://stats.premierleague.com/panel_b_alltime.query?q=goalkeeper_goals_conceded_all_seasons&start=1 \"Premier League official goalkeeper conceded stats\"]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On 30 January 2008, in a league match against Manchester United, he became the third player (after [[Gary Speed]] and [[Ryan Giggs]]) to cross the 500-match threshold.\n\nJames signed a one-year contract extension in May 2007, which kept him at [[Fratton Park]] until the end of the [[2008\u201309 Portsmouth F.C. season|2008\u201309 season]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/6648283.stm | title=James signs extended Pompey deal | work=BBC News | date=11 May 2007 | accessdate=2 January 2010}}</ref> James won the second major trophy of his career during that season, as Portsmouth claimed a 1\u20130 victory over [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in the [[2008 FA Cup Final]]. On 8 November 2008, he made his 100th appearance for Portsmouth.<ref>{{cite news |title=FULL MATCH REPORT: Sunderland 1 Portsmouth 2 |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/FULL-MATCH-REPORT-Sunderland-1.4677352.jp |publisher=Sunderland Echo |date=10 November 2008 |accessdate=19 May 2009 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120918055230/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/FULL-MATCH-REPORT-Sunderland-1.4677352.jp |archive-date=18 September 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHe holds the distinction of twice having been the record holder for consecutive Premier League appearances, with 159 during his Liverpool days from February 1994 to February 1998, and 166 between Manchester City and Portsmouth from 2006 to 2008; both streaks were eventually topped by [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]'s [[Frank Lampard]] and Tottenham Hotspur's [[Brad Friedel]], respectively.<ref name=\"friedel\">[http://www.birminghammail.net/birmingham-sport/aston-villa-fc/aston-villa-news/2008/11/24/i-play-for-aston-villa-not-for-myself-says-brad-friedel-97319-22326198/ I play for Aston Villa not for myself says Brad Friedel] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111123520/http://www.birminghammail.net/birmingham-sport/aston-villa-fc/aston-villa-news/2008/11/24/i-play-for-aston-villa-not-for-myself-says-brad-friedel-97319-22326198/ |date=11 January 2009 }} \u2013 Birmingham Mail, 29 November 2008, Retrieved on 29 November 2008</ref>\n\nOn 14 February 2009 against Manchester City, James made his 536th Premier League appearance, breaking [[Gary Speed]]'s all-time record.<ref name=\"speed\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thefa.com/England/All-Teams/Players/J/David-James | title=David James | publisher=thefa.com | accessdate=6 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2009, Times Online named James as the 15th greatest player in Portsmouth's history.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/portsmouth/article6059531.ece?token=null&offset=96&page=9 | title=Top 50 greatest Portsmouth players | location=London | work=The Times | first=Calvin | last=Shulman | date=21 April 2009 | accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nJames captained Portsmouth in the [[2009\u201310 FA Cup|FA Cup]] semi-final against Tottenham Hotspur where Portsmouth won 2\u20130 in extra time, describing the experience as \"superb\".<ref name=\"massive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/news/Chelsea-v-Portsmouth-FA-Cup-final-preview-David-James-eyes-up-FA-Cup-and-World-Cup-double-article423859.html |title=James eyes up FA Cup and World Cup double |publisher=mirrorfootball.co.uk |date=5 May 2010 |accessdate=6 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140115183138/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/news/Chelsea-v-Portsmouth-FA-Cup-final-preview-David-James-eyes-up-FA-Cup-and-World-Cup-double-article423859.html |archivedate=15 January 2014 |df= }}</ref> He also captained the team in [[FA Cup|the final]] as Portsmouth were beaten 1\u20130 by [[2009\u201310 Chelsea F.C. season|double winners]] [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].\n\nHis contract expired at the end of the 2009\u201310 season, and he expressed interest in succeeding [[Avram Grant]] as Portsmouth manager,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8696625.stm |title=Goalkeeper David James eyes Portsmouth manager role |work=BBC Sport |date=21 May 2010 |accessdate=28 July 2010}}</ref> though this came to nothing. The club offered him a new playing contract, but withdrew the offer after he failed to commit to the club; therefore, James left Portsmouth and became a [[Free Agent|free agent]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/8840717.stm |title=Portsmouth withdraw contract offer for David James |work=BBC Sport |date=21 July 2010 |accessdate=28 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Bristol City===\n[[File:David James taking goal kick.jpg|thumb|right|James playing for [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] in a [[Severnside derby]] against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], 2010]]\nJames signed a one-year contract with [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] on 30 July 2010, with the option of a second year.<ref name=\"bbc-news\">{{cite news|title=Bristol City capture England keeper David James |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bristol_city/8866521.stm|accessdate=30 July 2010|newspaper=BBC News|date=30 July 2010}}</ref> He stated that he hoped that his performances at the club would keep him on the radar for the [[England national football team|England team]] and that his decision to join them was motivated by a desire to be closer to his family home in [[Devon]].<ref>{{cite news|title=WHY I'VE JOINED CITY \u2013 DAVID |url=http://www.bcfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10327~2106915,00.html |accessdate=30 July 2010 |publisher=Bristol City |date=30 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802081941/http://www.bcfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10327~2106915%2C00.html |archivedate=2 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nJames' league debut for Bristol City came on 7 August 2010 in a 3\u20130 defeat to [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/8881366.stm | work=BBC News | title=Bristol City 0\u20133 Millwall | date=7 August 2010}}</ref> On 11 February 2011, the eve of his 850th club appearance, James announced he had signed a contract extension with the club until June 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bristol_city/9395420.stm | work=BBC News | title=David James earns new Bristol City contract | date=11 February 2011}}</ref> On 10 March 2012, James reached 900 club appearances in a game against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in the [[Severnside derby]], in which he was made captain as a mark of respect.<ref name=\"900app\">{{cite news|last=James|first=David|title=High-pressure game without a net when you hang up gloves|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2012/mar/10/david-james-900th-game|accessdate=13 March 2012|newspaper=guardian.co.uk|date=10 March 2012|location=London}}</ref>\n\nHe was released by Bristol City on 1 May 2012,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bcfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10327~2756132,00.html |title=Eight Players Leave Ashton Gate |date=1 May 2012 |publisher=Bristol City |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615003941/http://www.bcfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10327~2756132%2C00.html |archivedate=15 June 2012 |df= }}</ref> and in July 2012 began training with [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Pilnick |first=Brent |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18959167 |title=BBC Sport \u2013 Ex-England goalkeeper David James training with Exeter City |publisher=bbc.co.uk |date=2012-07-23 |accessdate=2013-06-08}}</ref>\n\n===Bournemouth===\nOn 27 September 2012, he arrived at [[Dean Court]] to train with [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]], signing a one-year deal to play for them the following day.<ref>{{cite news|title=David James signs for AFC Bournemouth until end of season|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19742976|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref> However, he did not see out the contract, leaving the club by mutual consent in March 2013 after making 19 appearances.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2292239/David-James-leaves-Bournemouth.html|title=James looking for club No 9 after parting company with Bournemouth by mutual consent|date=12 March 2013|newspaper=Daily Mail|location=London|first=David|last=Kent}}</ref>\n\n===\u00cdBV Vestmannaeyjar===\nOn 2 April 2013, James signed a contract with Icelandic club [[\u00cd\u00fer\u00f3ttabandalag Vestmannaeyja|\u00cdBV]] until the end of the [[2013 \u00darvalsdeild|2013 season]] in a joint player/coach capacity.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.mbl.is/sport/efstadeild/2013/04/02/david_james_er_mjog_spennandi/ | title=David James: Er mj\u00f6g spennandi | date=2 April 2013 | newspaper=[[Morgunbla\u00f0i\u00f0]]}}</ref> He linked up with former [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] teammate [[Hermann Hrei\u00f0arsson]], the manager of \u00cdBV. The \u00cdBV chairman stated that James was not being paid high wages, and that he was primarily playing out of kindness and to gain coaching experience.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://fotbolti.net/news/03-04-2013/segir-ad-david-james-se-ekki-a-haum-launum | title=Segir a\u00f0 David James s\u00e9 ekki \u00e1 h\u00e1um launum| date=3 April 2013 | publisher=fotbolti.net}}</ref> His arrival at \u00cdBV saw much higher attendances than in previous years.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.vb.is/eftirvinnu/84393/| title=Oft hagst\u00e6tt a\u00f0 f\u00e1 erlenda leikmenn| date=26 May 2013 | publisher=Vi\u00f0skiptabla\u00f0i\u00f0}}</ref> \u00cdBV ended the season in sixth position, and James announced his retirement from playing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24670325|title=David James: Former England keeper to coach at Luton Town|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=25 October 2013|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Kerala Blasters and retirement===\nHe was signed by [[Kerala Blasters FC]], owned by [[Sachin Tendulkar]], for the [[2014 Indian Super League season]] as a player-manager. He said \"I hope my involvement with ISL will be the start of something great.\"<ref name=\"KB\">{{cite news|title=David James set to have a blast with Sachin Tendulkar in ISL|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Sports/Football/Indian-Super-League/Interviews/David-James-set-to-have-a-blast-with-Sachin-Tendulkar-in-ISL/articleshow/40469918.cms|newspaper=Times of India|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> The team's first fixture on 13 October, in which James played, resulted in a 1\u20130 defeat at [[NorthEast United]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ganguily|first1=Abhishek|title=ISL: NorthEast United ride high on Koke, beat Kerala Blasters 1\u20130|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/ISL-NorthEast-United-ride-high-on-Koke-beat-Kerala-Blasters-1-0/articleshow/44808993.cms|accessdate=16 October 2014|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=13 October 2014}}</ref>\nHis team eventually became the runners up in the inaugural ISL tournament by losing to [[Atletico de Kolkata]] 1\u20130 in the finals.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} James retired at the end of the season.\n\n==International career==\n[[File:DaJa.JPG|thumb|right|James in [[England national football team|England]] colours, 2009]]\nAfter making one [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21]] appearance whilst at Watford, James made his full debut for [[Glenn Hoddle]]'s England in a [[friendly match|friendly]] against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] on 29 March 1997 when he was a Liverpool player. He kept his first international clean sheet as England beat Mexico 2\u20130 with goals from [[Teddy Sheringham]] and James' Liverpool teammate [[Robbie Fowler]]. He was in the provisional 28-man squad for [[Euro 2000]] before missing the final cut.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/may/22/newsstory.sport5|title=Euro 2000 provisional squads|work=The Guardian|date=22 May 2000 |accessdate=9 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nJames is the only black goalkeeper to represent England as a full international.<ref name=black>{{cite news |last1=Scott |first1=Matt |title=David James, England\u2019s first black goalkeeper, pours scorn on FA's stance in John Terry racism scandal |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/9603671/David-James-Englands-first-black-goalkeeper-pours-scorn-on-FAs-stance-in-John-Terry-racism-scandal.html |accessdate=22 September 2019 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=12 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor several years he had to play understudy to England's regular keeper, [[David Seaman]]. When Seaman was dropped after making a mistake against [[Republic of Macedonia national football team|FYR Macedonia]] in 2002, James became the new England number one. He retained his place in the England team even after West Ham's relegation to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] in 2003, and was the only player from outside the top flight to win an England cap between 1999 ([[Michael Gray (footballer)|Michael Gray]]) and 2007 ([[David Nugent]]). He went on to play in all of England's matches at [[2004 UEFA European Football Championship|Euro 2004]].\n\nJames was dropped from the starting XI after an error in a 2\u20132 [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] qualifying draw against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] in September 2004, his place being taken by Tottenham's [[Paul Robinson (goalkeeper)|Paul Robinson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-359636/Denmark-4-England-1.html |title=Denmark 4 England 1 &#124; Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date=2005-08-18 |accessdate=2013-06-08 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nJames came on as a half-time substitute and conceded all four goals in the 4\u20131 drubbing England suffered at the hands of [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] during a friendly on 17 August 2005 \u2013 their worst defeat in 25 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4154680.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; Internationals &#124; Denmark 4\u20131 England |work=BBC News |date=2005-08-17 |accessdate=2013-06-08}}</ref> James still remained part of the England squad, and was selected as the second-choice goalkeeper behind Robinson for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] in Germany, though he did not play.\n\nAlong with fellow veterans [[David Beckham]] and [[Sol Campbell]], James was dropped from the England squad at the start of [[Steve McClaren]]'s reign and was not called up during the [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307 season]]. He was recalled for the friendly with [[Germany national football team|Germany]] on 22 August 2007, over a year since first being omitted. James played the whole of the second half of England's 2\u20131 defeat to Germany as a substitute for Robinson. In so doing, he became the first Portsmouth player to play for the senior England team since [[Mark Hateley]] in 1984. However, [[Scott Carson]] was chosen ahead of both James and Robinson for the decisive Euro 2008 qualifier against Croatia on 21 November 2007. England lost the match 2-3, due to a fumble by Carson.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7103110.stm | title=England 2-3 Croatia|date=21 November 2007|first=Jonathan|last=Stevenson|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref> Following England's failure to qualify for [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]] McClaren was sacked as England manager and replaced by [[Fabio Capello]]. James was subsequently critical of McClaren's treatment of England's goalkeepers.<ref>''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/7111829.stm Keeper James hits out at McClaren]'' BBC Sport, 25 November 2007</ref>\n\nOn 7 February 2008, James was selected as goalkeeper for Capello's first match in charge, a friendly against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]. It was his first start for England since a friendly with [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] in May 2005.<ref>''[http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/Archive/default.htm?i=5088&pf=p&searchname=ja&ap=p&t=m England Senior Team Archive]'' TheFA.com</ref> James firmly re-established himself as England's first choice goalkeeper, starting in each of Capello's first 13 games in charge. Persistent injury problems over the following year left James' hopes of retaining the No. 1 spot for the [[2010 World Cup]] in doubt, with Capello stating he would only consider players who were 100% fit for his squad.<ref>''[https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/latest/2009/11/16/capello-warning-to-james-115875-21825553/]''</ref> After the [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|World Cup qualifier]] against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] on 1 April 2009, James did not start a match for England until the final friendly before the World Cup against [[Japan national football team|Japan]] on 30 May 2010.<ref>''[https://archive.today/20120714121600/http://thefa.com/England/MensSeniorTeam/Results.aspx]''.</ref>\n\n===2010 World Cup===\nPrior to the tournament, James was backed to reclaim the number one shirt by former England goalkeepers [[Gordon Banks]]<ref>''[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/may/19/david-james-world-cup-gordon-banks David James should start for England at World Cup, says Gordon Banks]''  guardian.co.uk, 19 May 2010</ref> and [[David Seaman]].<ref>''[http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/blogs/mirror-football-blog/David-Seaman-exclusive-Why-David-James-must-be-England-s-World-Cup-goalkeeper-The-Big-Interview-article241899.html David Seaman exclusive: Why David James must be England's World Cup goalkeeper \u2013 The Big Interview] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091205042000/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/blogs/mirror-football-blog/David-Seaman-exclusive-Why-David-James-must-be-England-s-World-Cup-goalkeeper-The-Big-Interview-article241899.html |date=5 December 2009 }}''  mirrorfootball.co.uk, 12 March 2010</ref>\n\nOn 3 June 2010, it was confirmed that James would be travelling to the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|World Cup Finals]] in South Africa, and would be allocated the number 1 jersey. He was the oldest footballer in the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.stv.tv/fifa-world-cup/180776-world-cup-squads-the-story-of-the-stats |title=World Cup squads: The story of the stats |publisher=Sport.stv.tv |date=2 June 2010 |accessdate=10 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007210159/http://sport.stv.tv/fifa-world-cup/180776-world-cup-squads-the-story-of-the-stats/ |archivedate=7 October 2011}}</ref> James was not selected for the first game of the World Cup against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]], with [[Robert Green]] instead starting in the England goal. However, Green made an error that allowed [[Clint Dempsey]] to score an equaliser that resulted in the game being drawn.<ref>{{cite news| author=Phil McNulty |title=England 1\u20131 USA |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_05|publisher=BBC |date=12 June 2010 |accessdate=13 June 2010 }}</ref> James returned to the starting line-up in the next game, keeping a clean sheet against [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] on 18 June 2010. In doing so James became the oldest ever World Cup debutant at 39 years and 321 days old.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/140/world-cup-2010/2010/07/02/2004616/world-cup-2010-david-james-is-oldest-debutant-david-villa |title=DONT PUBLISH: World Cup 2010: David James Is Oldest Debutant; David Villa Overtakes Thierry Henry |publisher=Goal.com |date=2010-07-02 |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref> Five days later, he kept another clean sheet as England won against [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]] 1\u20130 to ensure that they would reach the last 16, although they finished second in Group C behind the United States. They were eliminated in the following round after a [[Germany v England (2010)|4\u20131 defeat to Germany]].\n\n==Coaching career==\nCommenting on the comparatively low numbers of black players who become managers in English football, James said in 2012 that \"I struggle with the racist issue in football because I don't see it, and that's not because I've got my head in the sand. In the earlier days, yes, but the game's changed...If you don't want to go, an [''sic''] moan about not getting jobs, well, probably because you haven't been on the course is the reason why you haven't got a job.\"<ref name=black/>\n\n===Luton Town===\nFollowing a player-coach role at Icelandic side IBV earlier in the year October 2013 saw James join [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] in a coaching capacity in order to gain experience towards a [[UEFA]] A-licence qualification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lutontown.co.uk/news/article/david-james-2510-1135236.aspx |title=James on Luton |publisher=Luton Town F.C. |date= 25 October 2013 |accessdate= 18 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Kerala Blasters FC===\nJames was the player-manager of [[Kerala Blasters FC]] in the [[Indian Super League]] [[2014 Indian Super League season|2014 season]].<ref name=\"KB\"/> Utilising a distinctly British identity, signing players such as [[Stephen Pearson]] and [[Michael Chopra]], he took them to the ISL playoffs at the first attempt, after a 4th-place finish in the league phase. In the playoffs, extra time was needed to see off [[Chennaiyin FC|Chennaiyin]] 4\u20133 on aggregate, taking James and Kerala Blasters to the [[2014 Indian Super League final]], only to lose 1\u20130 to [[Atl\u00e9tico de Kolkata]]. James left the club at the end of his contract.\n\nJames returned to the helm of the club as their head coach a day after the sacking of [[Rene Meulensteen]] on 3 January 2018, following a string of poor performances.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He set about rebuilding the side in the January transfer window, releasing [[Mark Sifneos]] and signing [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] international midfielder [[Gu\u00f0j\u00f3n Baldvinsson]] on loan from [[Stjarnan]], along with appointing former [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] teammate [[Hermann Hrei\u00f0arsson]] as his assistant. Despite overseeing a turnaround in form, he could only guide the Blasters to 6th place at the end the [[2017\u201318 Indian Super League]] season, missing out on the play-offs.\n\nThe club started the [[2018\u201319 Indian Super League]] season with a victory, beating [[ATK (football club)|ATK]] 2\u20130 at [[Salt Lake Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/sports/isl-2018-19-david-james-faces-managerial-test-as-defence-heavy-kerala-blasters-look-to-go-all-the-way-5283651.html|title=ISL 2018-19: David James faces managerial test as defence-heavy Kerala Blasters look to go all the way - Firstpost|website=www.firstpost.com|access-date=2018-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/football/atk-vs-kerala-blasters-football-live-streaming-isl-2018-football-live-score-streaming-5379434/|title=ISL 2018 Highlights: Kerala Blasters begin campaign by beating ATK 2-0 in Kolkata|date=2018-09-29|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-09-29|language=en-US}}</ref> However this was followed by an 11-match winless run, which resulted in James' sacking in December 2018<ref name=\"Goal\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{{updated|27 January 2015}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballdatabase.com/index.php?page=player&Id=131&b=true&pn=David_James |title=JAMES (David James) \u2013 Portsmouth and England |publisher=Footballdatabase.com |accessdate=20 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=3869 |title=David James Career Stats |publisher=Soccerbase |date=28 December 2009 |accessdate=28 December 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100205181940/http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=3869 |archive-date=5 February 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/PlayerProfile/0,,12306~5495~2009,00.html |title=David James Career Stats (2) |publisher=Premier League |date=28 December 2009 |accessdate=28 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524160219/http://www.premierleague.com/page/PlayerProfile/0%2C%2C12306~5495~2009%2C00.html |archivedate=24 May 2010 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksi.is/mot/motalisti/felagsmadur/?pLeikmadurNr=289458&pListi=5|title=David Benjamin James|publisher=[[KS\u00cd|ksi.is]]|accessdate=5 May 2013}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup{{efn|Includes [[FA Cup]], [[Icelandic Men's Football Cup|Icelandic Cup]]}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!