2|\u2014||29||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!134!!0!!15!!0!!3!!0!!5!!0!!1!!0!!158!!0\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Bristol City F.C. season|2010\u201311]]\n|Championship\n|45||0||1||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||46||0\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Bristol City F.C. season|2011\u201312]]\n|Championship\n|36||0||1||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||38||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!81!!0!!2!!0!!1!!0!!colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014!!84!!0\n|-\n|[[A.F.C. Bournemouth|AFC Bournemouth]]\n|[[2012\u201313 A.F.C. Bournemouth season|2012\u201313]]\n|[[Football League One|League One]]\n|19||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014|||19||0\n|-\n|[[\u00cd\u00fer\u00f3ttabandalag Vestmannaeyja|\u00cdBV]]\n|[[2013 \u00darvalsdeild|2013]]\n|[[\u00darvalsdeild]]\n|17||0||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||4{{efn|name=UEL|Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||0||colspan=2|\u2014||23||0\n|-\n|[[Kerala Blasters FC|Kerala Blasters]]\n|[[2014 Kerala Blasters FC season|2014]]\n|[[Indian Super League]]\n|12||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||12||0\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Career total\n!817||0||60||0||44||0||35||0||2||0||958||0\n|}\n\n===International===\n<ref>{{NFT player|id=2174|name=David James|accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\" \n|+ Appearances and goals by national team and year\n|-\n! National team !! Year !! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n| rowspan=\"13\"|[[England national football team|England]]\n|-\n|1997||1||0\n|-\n|2000||1||0\n|-\n|2001||3||0\n|-\n|2002||5||0\n|-\n|2003||11||0\n|-\n|2004||9||0\n|-\n|2005||3||0\n|-\n|2006||1||0\n|-\n|2007||1||0\n|-\n|2008||10||0\n|-\n|2009||4||0\n|-\n|2010||4||0\n|-\n! colspan=2|Total||53||0\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:David Jamesgoalkeeper2.jpg|150px|thumb|left|James in 2005]]\nJames was brought up in [[Welwyn Garden City]], attending the Sir Frederic Osborn School.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/magazine/story/0,,2097416,00.html | title=Saving the planet| accessdate=18 August 2007 | work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Lucy | last=Siegle | date=10 June 2007}}</ref> He is of mixed Jamaican and English descent, and spent part of his childhood in Jamaica.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/may/22/newsstory.sport3|title=Interview: Paula Cocozza meets David James|first=Paula|last=Cocozza|date=22 May 2004|website=the Guardian}}</ref> He has four children with his former wife Tanya,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/david-james-new-goal-in-life-that-nearly-made-me-give-up-the-game-417295.html |title=David James: New goal in life that 'nearly made me give up the game' |work=Independent|date= 24 September 2006|accessdate=20 June 2010 | location=London}}</ref> whom he divorced in 2005, and as of June 2007 lived in [[Chudleigh]], [[Devon]] with his partner, Amanda Salmon.<ref>{{cite news|author=Lucy Siegle |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2007/jun/10/ethicalliving.lifeandhealth2 |title=Saving the planet: David James &#124; Environment &#124; The Observer |newspaper=Guardian |date= 10 June 2007|accessdate=2013-06-08 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nJames has gained attention for modelling assignments, first with [[Giorgio Armani]] in 1995,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-08/02/content_6465890.htm | title=Armani decks out Chelsea stars| accessdate=18 August 2007}}</ref> and with [[H&M]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/fashion/2005/03/29/footballerfashion/ |title=Fit footballers score in sexy fashion ads |accessdate=18 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930180438/http://www.hellomagazine.com/fashion/2005/03/29/footballerfashion/ |archivedate=30 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nJames was known for experimenting with his hairstyle. In May 2007, a \"Who Ate All the Pies\" column ridiculed him, among David Beckham and others,<ref>{{cite web|title=Pies ridicules hair: Beckham, James, et al|url=http://www.whoateallthepies.tv/category/horror_hair/page/10|accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> for \"backcombed efforts\",<ref>{{cite news|title=James photo Nov 2006|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/6185270.stm|accessdate=20 April 2013 | work=BBC News|date=26 November 2006}}</ref> and likened a previous November 2006 cut to fictional character [[Clark Kent]],<ref>{{cite web|title=James like Clark Kent|url=http://www.whoateallthepies.tv/horror_hair/1040/horror_hair_dav.html|accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> both captured by BBC ''[[Match of the Day]]''.\n\nDuring the 2003 off-season, James was a guest at the training camp of [[American football]] team the [[Miami Dolphins]], where he studied their training and conditioning methods.<ref>{{cite news|title=David James visits NFL camp |url=http://www.nfluk.com/features-display.php?id=142 |publisher=NFLUK.com |accessdate=29 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927022634/http://www.nfluk.com/features-display.php?id=142 |archivedate=27 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nJames was a 20-a-day smoker during his early career, having taken up the habit while sidelined with injury at the age of 15 and quit for the new millennium. He fronted an anti-smoking campaign in 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last1=James |first1=David |title=It's time for the whole game to stub out my filthy habit |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/mar/16/sport.comment4 |accessdate=22 September 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=16 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Charity work===\nIn 2005, James visited the south eastern African nation of [[Malawi]] to help raise [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] awareness.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article597684.ece | title=So much for the image of lazy, rich players as Farmer James cultivates new talent in Malawi| accessdate=18 August 2007 | location=London | work=The Times | first=Matt | last=Dickinson | date=29 November 2005}}</ref> He subsequently set up the David James Foundation in order to help [[maize]] farmers in Malawi develop more efficient production techniques.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djf.org.uk/index.php?page=what-we-do |title=What We Do |publisher=David James Foundation |accessdate=2013-10-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807150143/http://www.djf.org.uk/index.php?page=what-we-do |archivedate=7 August 2013 |df= }}</ref> The foundation also aims to give teenagers the skills, such as mechanical and construction skills, needed to go out and work. James has also made connections with [[West Exe Technology College]], [[Exeter]]. This college has brought to his attention the Malawian charity, Friends of Mulanje Orphans.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.davidjamesfoundation.org.uk/index.asp |title=David James Foundation |accessdate=26 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009052018/http://www.davidjamesfoundation.org.uk/index.asp |archivedate=9 October 2007 |df= }}</ref> The foundation funds the David James Foundation Scholarship at the [[University of Westminster]], which funds a student from Malawi to study for a [[master's degree]] at Westminster.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.davidjamesfoundation.org.uk/news.asp?id=1 |title=DJF secures Malawi scholarship at University of Westminster |publisher=David James Foundation |accessdate=9 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009052042/http://www.davidjamesfoundation.org.uk/news.asp?id=1 |archivedate=9 October 2007}}</ref> The charity has been supported by the [[Institution of Chemical Engineers]] (IChemE).<ref name=\"chem\">[http://cms.icheme.org/mainwebsite/general-barafc3d75d.aspx?map=60fe13a7d7c59bce19cbb030d60f127e FA Cup winner unites with chemical engineers to tackle poverty]{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}&nbsp;\u2013 icheme.org, 22 May 2008, Retrieved on 29 November 2008</ref> James is also a global ambassador for the [[Special Olympics]] and works with Access Sport to provide sports provision in deprived areas of the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/ethicalawards/story/0,,1988340,00.html|title=Ethical awards 2008: David James|newspaper=The Observer|date=14 January 2007|accessdate=9 March 2008 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Portsmouth |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/portsmouth/4615380/David-James-earns-big-hand-for-longevity.html |title=David James earns big hand for longevity |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date= 13 February 2009|accessdate=2013-10-26 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Art and writing===\nJames is an avid artist, and has auctioned several of his paintings for charity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/ex-england-goalkeeper-david-james-9234022|title=Ex-England goalkeeper David James is a fine artist - and he's auctioning this iconic image off for charity|first=Mike|last=Walters|date=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being an art lover, he writes a regular column for ''[[The Observer]]'' newspaper, and donates his article fee to charity.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/davidjames | title=The Guardian&nbsp;\u2013 David James profile | newspaper=The Observer|accessdate=18 April 2010 | location=London | date=30 November 2007}}</ref> James was also the illustrator on the children's book ''Harry's Magic Pockets: The Circus'' written by his friend, Steve Pearson.<ref>{{cite news |title=Circus star James |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/circus-star-james-656924 |work=Daily Mirror |date=28 September 2008 |accessdate=12 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Bankruptcy===\nIn May 2014 James was declared [[Bankruptcy|bankrupt]]. Despite earning an estimated \u00a320m from his footballing career, owning several properties and having a lucrative contract modeling for Armani, James' debts had built up since his divorce from his wife, Tanya, in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/fameandfortune/10835644/Former-England-footballer-David-James-declares-himself-bankrupt.html|title=Former England footballer David James declares himself bankrupt|work=Daily Telegraph|date=16 May 2014|accessdate=16 May 2014|author=Caldwell, Kyle}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, James placed for sale hundreds of items of football [[memorabilia]] collected during his career, to pay off the debts. Items included 150 signed shirts, shorts and match balls as well as his customised [[Vauxhall Astra]] van and [[Raleigh Chopper]] bikes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-29895649|title=Bankrupt goalkeeper David James auctions football memorabilia|work=BBC News|date=4 November 2014|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Keeper David James: Football memorabilia sold off|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-30109281|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 November 2014|date=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Media career==\nShortly before [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]], James presented a [[BBC]] programme entitled ''Euro's Most Shocking Moments'' alongside [[Richard Bacon (broadcaster)|Richard Bacon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Euro's most shocking moments|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01j73yq|accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2013, it was announced that James would become a TV pundit for [[BT Sport]]'s coverage of [[Premier League]] and [[Conference Premier]] matches.<ref>{{cite news|author=Nik Simon |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2382410/David-James-stat-man-ready-freshen-things-BT-Sport.html |title=David James the stat-man is ready to freshen things up with BT Sport |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |date=2013-08-01 |accessdate=2013-10-26 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nJames worked as a pundit for [[Eurosport]] at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]], and for India's [[Sony Ten]] at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].\n\nIn July 2019, it was announced that James would participate as a contestant on the [[Strictly Come Dancing (series 17)|seventeenth series]] of ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2019/hulk|title=David James MBE is the first contestant confirmed or Strictly Come Dancing 2019|publisher=BBC|date=31 July 2019}}</ref> He was partnered with [[Nadiya Bychkova]] and, on 20 October 2019, was the fourth celebrity to be eliminated after a dance-off with [[Mike Bushell]] and [[Katya Jones]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yeates |first1=Cydney |title=Strictly Come Dancing\u2019s David James becomes fourth celebrity to be evicted |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/10/20/strictly-come-dancings-david-james-becomes-fourth-celebrity-to-be-evicted-10950311/ |accessdate=21 October 2019 |work=Metro |date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Liverpool'''<ref name=SW>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/david-james/173/|title=D. James|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>\n* [[EFL Cup|Football League Cup]]: [[1994\u201395 Football League Cup|1994\u201395]]\n\n'''Portsmouth'''<ref name=SW/>\n* [[FA Cup]]: [[2007\u201308 FA Cup|2007\u201308]]\n\n'''Individual'''\n* [[Toulon Tournament]] Best Goalkeeper: 1991<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/youths-descend-on-toulon_sto725522/story.shtml|title=Youthful talents convene in Toulon|publisher=Eurosport|date=1 June 2005|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{FIFA player}}\n* {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080730222943/http://www.portsmouthfc.co.uk/index.php?cms_ref=squad_players |date=30 July 2008 |title=Player profile at Portsmouth football club}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* [http://sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/searchresults.asp?ButtonLeap=0&countryLinkDescription=+matching+sear