,\n\t\"axes\": [\n\t\t{\n\t\t\t\"type\": \"x\",\n\t\t\t\"scale\": \"x\",\n\t\t\t\"title\": \"days\"\n\t\t},\n\t\t{\n\t\t\t\"type\": \"y\",\n\t\t\t\"scale\": \"y\",\n\t\t\t\"title\": \"cases\"\n\t\t}\n\t],\n\t\"marks\": [\n\t\t{\n\t\t\t\"type\": \"line\",\n\t\t\t\"from\": {\n\t\t\t\t\"data\": \"table\"\n\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\"properties\": {\n\t\t\t\t\"enter\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"scale\": \"x\",\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"field\": \"x\"\n\t\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"scale\": \"y\",\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"field\": \"y\"\n\t\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y2\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"scale\": \"y\",\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"value\": 0\n\t\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t\t\"interpolate\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"value\": \"monotone\"\n\t\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t\t\"stroke\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"value\": \"steelblue\"\n\t\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t\t\"strokeWidth\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"value\": 3\n\t\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t]\n}</graph>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n===March 2020===\nOn March 13, 2020, [[Prime Minister of Aruba|Prime Minister]] [[Evelyn Wever-Croes]] announced the first two confirmed cases of coronavirus on the island.<ref name=\"FirstCases\">{{Cite news |url=https://24ora.com/dos-caso-di-coronavirus-na-aruba-di-cual-un-ta-arubiano/?utm_source=dlvr.it&utm_medium=twitter |title=DOS CASO DI CORONAVIRUS NA ARUBA DI CUAL UN TA ARUBIANO |date=13 March 2020 |work=24ora.com |language=Papiamento|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs a result, the country restricted entry of all individuals coming from [[Europe]] via air and seaports \u2013 starting on March15 and in effect until March 31 \u2013 with the exception of those who are Aruban citizens.<ref name=\"FirstCases\"/> They also suspended public and private school classes for the week of March 16, as well as all large-scale public gatherings.\n\nOn March 15, 2020, at approximately 8pm AST, Aruba's Prime Minister Evelyn Wever-Croes announced that there would be a lockdown on all inbound international travel commencing at midnight of March 16, 2020 and ending on March 31, 2020. An exception to this inbound travel lockdown would be granted to Aruba residents. A travel advisory would also be instituted for residents, advising against outbound travel at this time. To this date Aruba had two confirmed Corona Virus cases. It is important to note that this lockdown does not apply to outbound travel for international travelers currently in Aruba \u2013 they will be able to take their return flight home.\n\nOn March 16 to 17th the 3rd case of the coronavirus was reported, a doctor who recently travelled to New York for her vacation. She did not show any symptoms, but was tested, and the results of the test showed she was positive for the virus.\n\nMarch 17, 2020 \u2013 Fourth case of coronavirus announced. Aruba's Prime Minister Evelyn Wever-Croes has just announced a fourth case of COVID-19 coronavirus in Aruba. The person who tested positive for the coronavirus is a tourist.\n\nMarch 20, 2020 \u2013 Fifth case of coronavirus announced. The patient is an employee of the airport, who arrived back from New York, where he was on vacation. This was discovered a day after there was public protest over the lack of measures on the airport to protect employees against contagion.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=24 luchthavenmedewerkers uit voorzorg in quarantaine|date=March 20, 2020|work=Amigoe Aruba|access-date=|url-status=live|publisher=Amigoe}}</ref>\n\nMarch 21, 2020 \u2013 Three more cases have been announced, bringing the total to eight. It concerns two people from outside of Aruba (one from [[New York City|New York]] and one from [[Miami]]). The third case is possibly the first locally transmitted case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://24ora.com/a-subi-di-5-pa-8-caso-di-localnan-confirma-cu-coronavirus/|title=A subi di 5 pa 8 caso di localnan confirma cu Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=2020-03-21|website=24ora.com|language=papiamento|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nMarch 22, 2020 \u2013 A ninth case is now known to be a CMB employee, who had returned from travel to the USA. He has been to work only a relatively short time and has had no contact with customers. CMB has now closed the branch until further notice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18765|title=CMB a reacciona tocante empleado cu a test positivo pa coronavirus|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-03-23|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nMarch 23, 2020 \u2013 Again three more cases have been announced. They are two locally transmitted cases, and one brought to Aruba from Colombia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18767|title=Aruba tin 3 caso nobo positivo di coronavirus|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-03-23|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nMarch 24, 2020 \u2013 Five new cases are reported, bringing the total to 17 now. Though this looks like a big jump the testing has been increased from 20 persons to 40 per day. Of these 5 cases, three are locally transmitted. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18792|title=Aruba awor tin 17 caso positivo di coronavirus|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-03-24|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nMarch 25, 2020 \u2013 Only two new cases are reported, totaling 19. It's possible this is the effect of the drastic measures that were taken earlier this month, such as the ongoing curfew. It concerns one imported case from Colombia, and one locally transmitted case. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18816|title=Aruba awor tin total di 19 caso positivo pa coronavirus|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-03-25|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nMarch 26, 2020 \u2013 Nine new cases are reported, totaling 28. This is likely related to the increased testing, which has now doubled (from 50 per day to 100 per day). Several cases are employees of Respaldo, the mental health institute of Aruba, which is situated close to the hospital. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.visitaruba.com/news/general/corona-virus-and-travel-to-aruba/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) and Travel to Aruba {{!}} VisitAruba News|date=2020-03-26|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nMarch 27, 2020 \u2013 Five new cases on this day are reported, bringing the island to 33 cases. All of those are locally transmitted case, and one of those working at Respaldo, where people were infected a day before. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18845|title=Aruba su casonan positivo di coronavirus a bira 33|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-03-27|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nMarch 28, 2020 \u2013 Thirteen new cases have been reported, the highest to date, with a current total of 46 now. There is no record yet as to the origin of these new cases. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18852|title=Cu 13 caso extra awe, tin 46 caso positivo di coronavirus na Aruba|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-03-28|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nMarch 29, 2020 \u2013 Only four new cases this day (total 50). A possible cause is the effect of public measures that started March 15. Initially the number was set to six cases, but two of those appeared to be false positives. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18861|title=Update: Cifra di caso positivo di coronavirus pa Aruba ahusta na 50|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-03-29|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nMarch 30, 2020 \u2013 No new cases have been reported. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arubacovid19.org/|title=Aruba Covid-19 Information|website=Aruba Covid-19|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nMarch 31, 2020 \u2013 Unfortunately another increase of 5 cases (total 55). Four patients are hospitalized, of which one in medium care unit, and one in intensive care unit. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18891|title=Cuater pashent cu coronavirus ta hospitalisa|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-03-31|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\nApril 1, 2020 \u2013 No new cases.\n\nApril 2, 2020 \u2013 5 new cases are reported, totaling 60 now. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18916|title=Aruba tin total di 60 caso positivo di coronavirus awor|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-04-02|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nApril 3, 2020 \u2013 2 new cases have been reported, totaling 62 now. Nine patients are hospitalized. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18931|title=Cantidad di pashent hospitalisa cu coronavirus na Aruba a bira 9|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-04-03|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nApril 4, 2020 \u2013 again only 2 new cases have been reported, totaling 64 now. A rumor that over 40 cases had been found in Savaneta was quickly discredited by the national health services (DVG). <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18934|title=Casonan positivo di coronavirus a subi te na 64|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-04-04|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nApril 5, 2020 \u2013 No new cases. It looks like the start of flattening the curve, but we'll have to wait a few more days to have a stronger conclusion.\n\nApril 6, 2020 \u2013 7 new cases have been reported. Up to this point 910 persons have been tested, of which 838 have resulted negative, and one result is still pending. <ref name=\"upd_04-07\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18947|title=Aruba tin total di 71 caso positivo di coronavirus|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-04-06|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nApril 7, 2020 \u2013 3 new cases, bringing the total to 74 now. 14 people have recovered, so the total number of active cases is 60. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18957|title=Aruba su casonan positivo di coronavirus a yega 74 total|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-04-07|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nApril 8, 2020 - 3 new cases bringing the total to 77 now. There have been no new recoveries, thus the number of active cases is 63. <ref name=\"upd0408\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18971|title=Aruba su casonan positivo di coronavirus a bira 77|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-04-08|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Medische zending naar Sint Maarten (Covid-19).jpg|thumb|Medical shipment to [[Sint Maarten]]]]\nApril 9, 2020 - 5 new cases bringing the total to 82 now. There have been 6 new recoveries, therefore the number of active cases is 62. <ref name=\"upd0409\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18985|title=Aruba ta conoce 5 caso nobo positivo di coronavirus|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-04-09|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> The United States announced a repatriation flight for stranded in Americans. <ref name=\"upd0410\" />\n\nApril 10, 2020 - 4 more cases test positive and there have been 5 more recoveries. The current number of active cases is 59. 1,058 people have been tested thus far. <ref name=\"upd0410\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.visitaruba.com/news/general/corona-virus-and-travel-to-aruba/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) and Travel to Aruba|website=Visit Aruba|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n<br>\nRespirators, medicine and protective equipment is being flown to Aruba, [[Bonaire]] and [[Cura\u00e7ao]] by the Dutch government. The shipment will contain 12 ICU beds for Aruba. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.rijksdienstcn.com/latest/news/2020/april/10/30-respirators-medicines-and-protective-equipment-for-care-coronavirus-patients-to-aruba-bonaire-and-curacao|title=30 respirators, medicines and protective equipment for care coronavirus patients to Aruba, Bonaire and Curacao|website=Rijksdienst Caribisch Nederland|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nApril 11, 2020 - 4 more cases bringing the total to 92, and 2 more recoveries. The current number of active cases is now 63. <ref name=\"upd0411\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.visitaruba.com/news/general/corona-virus-and-travel-to-aruba/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) and Travel to Aruba|website=Visit Aruba|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n<br>\nAruba is disappointed with the emergency aid from the Netherlands. Aruba can borrow about 21 million euros, but had asked for 200 million euro. Prime Minister Croes said that she appreciated the loan, but did not agree, because the island is largely dependent on tourism. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.curacaochronicle.com/post/local/aruba-and-curacao-not-happy-with-the-dutch-emergency-aid-loan/|title=Aruba and Cura\u00e7ao not happy with the Dutch emergency aid loan|website=Cura\u00e7ao Chronicle|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nApril 12, 2020 - No new cases, 3 more recoveries bringing the number of active cases to 60. <ref name=\"upd0412\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arubacovid19.org/|title=Covid-19 Coronavirus|website=ArubaCovid19.org|language=pap|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n== Public measures ==\nMarch 15, 2020 - It was decided to close schools for the week of 16 to 20 of March. In actual effect this would only be a close of an additional two school days, since 18,19 and 20 were already closed in lieu of the national holiday (Aruban Flag day March 18).\n\nMarch 17, 2020 - It was decided to close all schools until the end of March, 2020. Note: This was only two days after the previous order to close schools for only one week. Schools are asked to make a plan for online education to minimize impact.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ea.aw/pages/coronavirus/|title=Ense\u00f1ansa Aruba|last=|first=|date=March 21, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMarch 19, 2020 - As of March 21, 2020 an indefinite curfew was set, from 9PM until 6AM every day. Violations can be met with fines up to AWG 10,000 (over US$5000).  In addition all shops need to be closed by 8PM every day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.overheid.aw/actualidad/noticia_47171/item/decisionnan-tuma-pa-gobierno-relaciona-cu-e-crisis-di-coronavirus-covid-19_48506.html|title=Curfew on Aruba starting March 21, 2020|last=|first=|date=March 19, 2020|website=Gobierno.aw - official government website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The country is in 'lockdown' meaning all travel of persons to the island is prohibited. Empty planes are still allowed to land in order to take people, e.g. tourists, off the island in order to return home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arubacovid19.org/ddg|title=Official Aruba COVID-19 response website|last=|first=|date=March 21, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMarch 25, 2020 - After the curfew was set, journalists rallied against this decision, and wrote letters to international organization for support, which they also received. The prime minister afterwards declared the press will be allowed on the streets during the curfew, but only 3 designated members of the press will be assigned, and should be ready to be stopped by police and properly identify themselves as members of the press. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18795|title=Prensa ta permiti awor pa traha durante toque de queda tambe|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-03-24|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nMarch 26, 2020  - Starting Sunday March 29, a mandatory \u2018shelter in place\u2019 order will be active, which means nobody can leave the house for anything but the most essential activities, such as groceries and doctor's visits. Sports will also be allowed, as long as people keep distance, as this is essential to general health. This order will be maintained for at least two weeks. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noticiacla.com/news/18832|title=Entrante diadomingo, ciudadanonan ta prohibi pa sali di cas (Shelter-in-place)|last=NoticiaCla|date=2020-03-26|website=NoticiaCla|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nApril 7, 2020 \u2013 The government of Aruba strengthens the current shelter in place for the Easter weekend. The change affects Good Friday and Easter Sunday. On these days all businesses will be closed, with exception of take-away service at restaurants, drive thru and delivery, gas stations, doctors and pharmacies. In addition it is not permitted to go to the beach and a ban on gatherings of 4 or more people. Only groups of a maximum of three are allowed and all should be living under one roof. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arubacovid19.org/post/conferencia-di-prensa-di-departamento-di-salud-publico-ta-keda-posponi-durante-semana-santa|title=Conferencia di prensa di Departamento di Salud Publico ta keda posponi durante Semana Santa.|last=Covid-19|first=Aruba|date=2020-04-09|website=Aruba Covid-19|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==External link==\n* [https://www.arubacovid19.org/ Official Covid 19 site]\n* [https://www.consulytic.com/corona Dashboard Caribbean]\n* [https://www.visitaruba.com/news/general/corona-virus-and-travel-to-aruba/ Aruba Tourist Agency]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Dutch Caribbean|Aruba]]\n[[Category:2020 in Aruba]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Aruba]]\n", "name_user": "KittenKlub", "label": "safe", "comment": "+map", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Aruba"}
{"title_page": "Valley of the Gods", "text_new": "[[File:Valley of the Gods, near Bluff, Utah.jpg|thumb|Valley of the Gods]]\nThe '''Valley of the Gods''' is a scenic [[sandstone]] valley near [[Mexican Hat, Utah|Mexican Hat]] in [[San Juan County, Utah|San Juan County]], southeastern [[Utah]], United States. Formerly part of [[Bears Ears National Monument]], Valley of the Gods is located north of [[Monument Valley]] across the [[San Juan River (Colorado River tributary)|San Juan River]] and has rock formations similar to those in Monument Valley with tall, reddish brown [[mesa]]s, [[butte]]s, [[Pinnacle (geology)|towers]] and [[mushroom rock]]s{{emdash}}remnants of an ancient landscape.<ref name=utah.com>{{cite web|title=Valley of the Gods Brochure|url=http://www.utah.com/monumentvalley/ValleyOfTheGods.htm|publisher=Utah Travel Industry Website|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=blm>{{cite web|title=Valley of the Gods|url=https://www.blm.gov/download/file/fid/3738|publisher=Bureau of Land Management|access-date=4 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204074646/https://www.blm.gov/download/file/fid/3738|archive-date=4 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 4, 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] issued a proclamation that reduced the area of Bears Ears National Monument, proclaimed by President [[Barack Obama]] in December 2016, with new monument boundaries that exclude the Valley of the Gods. The area remains protected public land administered as an [[Area of Critical Environmental Concern]] and managed by the [[Bureau of Land Management]], as it was before the monument designation.\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Valley of the Gods stones.jpg|thumb|Sandstone towers]]\nThe Valley of the Gods may be toured via a {{convert|17|mi|adj=on}} gravel road (San Juan County Road 242) that winds around the formations. The road is rather steep and bumpy in parts but is passable by non-[[four-wheel drive]] vehicles in dry weather. The western end joins [[Utah State Route 261]] shortly before its {{convert|1200|ft|adj=on}} ascent up [[Cedar Mesa]] at Moki Dugway, while the eastern end starts {{convert|9|mi|spell=in}} from the town of Mexican Hat along [[U.S. Route 163]] and heads north, initially crossing flat, open land and following the course of Lime Creek, a seasonal wash, before turning west toward the buttes and pinnacles.<ref name=utah.com/> In addition to the gravel road, the area is also crisscrossed by off-road dirt trails.\n\nThe valley is public land managed by the [[Bureau of Land Management]]. No entrance fee is charged and no services are provided in the valley. [[Dispersed Camping|Dispersed camping]] is permitted at previously disturbed sites, though campfires are not allowed.<ref name=blm/><ref name=blm2>[https://www.blm.gov/tag/valley-gods \"Valley of the Gods\"]. ''blm.gov''. [[Bureau of Land Management|BLM]]. Retrieved December 9, 2017.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe valley has been used as the backdrop for western movies, commercials and television shows including two episodes of the BBC science fiction show ''[[Doctor Who]]'': \"[[The Impossible Astronaut]]\" and \"[[Day of the Moon]]\", the second of which includes an explicit on-screen reference to the filming location.<ref name=blm/><ref name=utah.com/>\n\nThe 1984-1987 CBS TV show ''[[Airwolf]]'' is mistakenly identified as being filmed in Valley of the Gods due to it being mentioned in the pilot episode but was actually filmed in [[Monument Valley]].\n\n{{wide image|VOG,UT.jpg|600px|<center>Aerial view of the Valley of the Gods</center>}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://www.blm.gov/visit/search-details/269135/1 Official BLM site]\n*[http://www.americansouthwest.net/utah/mexican_hat/valley_of_the_gods.html Valley of the Gods on American Southwest net]\n\n{{coord|37|14|11|N|109|48|49|W|type:city_region:US-UT|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valley Of The Gods}}\n[[Category:Colorado Plateau]]\n[[Category:Landforms of San Juan County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Rock formations of Utah]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in San Juan County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Utah]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Valley of the Gods, near Bluff, Utah.jpg|thumb|Valley of the Gods]]\nThe '''Valley of the Gods''' is a scenic [[sandstone]] valley near [[Mexican Hat, Utah|Mexican Hat]] in [[San Juan County, Utah|San Juan County]], southeastern [[Utah]], United States. Formerly part of [[Bears Ears National Monument]], Valley of the Gods is located north of [[Monument Valley]] across the [[San Juan River (Colorado River tributary)|San Juan River]] and has rock formations similar to those in Monument Valley with tall, reddish brown [[mesa]]s, [[butte]]s, [[Pinnacle (geology)|towers]] and [[mushroom rock]]s{{emdash}}remnants of an ancient landscape.<ref name=utah.com>{{cite web|title=Valley of the Gods Brochure|url=http://www.utah.com/monumentvalley/ValleyOfTheGods.htm|publisher=Utah Travel Industry Website|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=blm>{{cite web|title=Valley of the Gods|url=https://www.blm.gov/download/file/fid/3738|publisher=Bureau of Land Management|access-date=4 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204074646/https://www.blm.gov/download/file/fid/3738|archive-date=4 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 4, 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] issued a proclamation that reduced the area of Bears Ears National Monument, proclaimed by President [[Barack Obama]] in December 2016, with new monument boundaries that exclude the Valley of the Gods. The area remains protected public land administered as an [[Area of Critical Environmental Concern]] and managed by the [[Bureau of Land Management]], as it was before the monument designation.\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Valley of the Gods stones.jpg|thumb|Sandstone towers]]\nThe Valley of the Gods may be toured via a {{convert|17|mi|adj=on}} gravel road (San Juan County Road 242) that winds around the formations. The road is rather steep and bumpy in parts but is passable by non-[[four-wheel drive]] vehicles in dry weather. The western end joins [[Utah State Route 261]] shortly before its {{convert|1200|ft|adj=on}} ascent up [[Cedar Mesa]] at Moki Dugway, while the eastern end starts {{convert|9|mi|spell=in}} from the town of Mexican Hat along [[U.S. Route 163]] and heads north, initially crossing flat, open land and following the course of Lime Creek, a seasonal wash, before turning west toward the buttes and pinnacles.<ref name=utah.com/> In addition to the gravel road, the area is also crisscrossed by off-road dirt trails.\n\nThe valley is public land managed by the [[Bureau of Land Management]]. No entrance fee is charged and no services are provided in the valley. [[Dispersed Camping|Dispersed camping]] is permitted at previously disturbed sites, though campfires are not allowed.<ref name=blm/><ref name=blm2>[https://www.blm.gov/tag/valley-gods \"Valley of the Gods\"]. ''blm.gov''. [[Bureau of Land Management|BLM]]. Retrieved December 9, 2017.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe valley has been used as the backdrop for western movies, commercials and television shows including two episodes of the BBC science fiction show ''[[Doctor Who]]'': \"[[The Impossible Astronaut]]\" and \"[[Day of the Moon]]\", the second of which includes an explicit on-screen reference to the filming location.<ref name=blm/><ref name=utah.com/>\n\nThe 1984-1987 CBS TV show ''[[Airwolf]]'' is often mistakenly identified as being filmed in Valley of the Gods due to an in episode mention but was filmed in [[Monument Valley]].\n\n{{wide image|VOG,UT.jpg|600px|<center>Aerial view of the Valley of the Gods</center>}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://www.blm.gov/visit/search-details/269135/1 Official BLM site]\n*[http://www.americansouthwest.net/utah/mexican_hat/valley_of_the_gods.html Valley of the Gods on American Southwest net]\n\n{{coord|37|14|11|N|109|48|49|W|type:city_region:US-UT|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valley Of The Gods}}\n[[Category:Colorado Plateau]]\n[[Category:Landforms of San Juan County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Rock formations of Utah]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in San Juan County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Utah]]\n", "name_user": "Bluecoat2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valley_of_the_Gods"}
